[3] sCJD: differential diagnosis
Date: Tue 24 Sep 2012
Source: Archives of Neurology [summ., edited]
http://archneur.jamanetwork.com/article.aspx?articleid=1362174


[Ref: Paterson RW, Torres-Chae CC, Kuo AL, et al: Differential Diagnosis of Jakob-Creutzfeldt Disease. Arch Neurol. 2012 Sep 24:1-5. doi: 10.1001/archneurol.2013.79. [Epub ahead of print]
-------------------------------------------
Abstract
--------
Objectives: To identify the misdiagnoses of patients with sporadic Jakob-Creutzfeldt disease (sCJD) during the course of their disease and determine which medical specialties saw patients with sCJD prior to the correct diagnosis being made and at what point in the disease course a correct diagnosis was made.

Participants: 163 serial patients over a 5.5-year period who ultimately had pathologically proven sCJD. The study used the subset of 97 patients for whom we had adequate medical records.

Main outcome measures: Other diagnoses considered in the differential diagnosis and types of medical specialties assessing patients with sCJD.

Results: 97 subjects' records were used in the final analysis. The most common disease categories of misdiagnosis were neurodegenerative, autoimmune/paraneoplastic, infectious, and toxic/metabolic disorders. The most common individual misdiagnoses were viral encephalitis, paraneoplastic disorder, depression, vertigo, Alzheimer's disease, stroke, unspecified dementia, central nervous system vasculitis, peripheral neuropathy, and Hashimoto encephalopathy. The physicians who most commonly made these misdiagnoses were primary care physicians and neurologists; in the 18 percent of patients who were diagnosed correctly at their 1st assessment, the diagnosis was almost always by a neurologist. The mean time from onset to diagnosis was 7.9 months, an average of two-thirds of the way through their disease course.

Conclusions: Diagnosis of sCJD is quite delayed. When evaluating patients with rapidly progressive dementia with suspected neurodegenerative, autoimmune, infectious, or toxic/metabolic etiology, sCJD should also be included in the differential diagnosis, and appropriate diagnostic tests, such as diffusion brain magnetic resonance imaging, should be considered. Primary care physicians and neurologists need improved training in sCJD diagnosis.

--
Communicated by:
Terry S Singeltary Sr
<flounder9@verizon.net>

[Interested readers should access the original text via the source URL above to view the entire text, figures, tables, and references cited.

This analysis indicates that the most common disease categories of misdiagnosis were neurodegenerative, autoimmune/paraneoplastic, infectious, and toxic/metabolic disorders. The most common individual misdiagnoses were viral encephalitis, paraneoplastic disorder, depression, vertigo, Alzheimer's disease, stroke, unspecified dementia, central nervous system vasculitis, peripheral neuropathy, and Hashimoto encephalopathy. Clearly improvements in the diagnosis of sCJD are required. - Mod.CP]

