[4] Prions, zinc uptake, and disease
Date: Wed 17 Oct 2012
Source: MSN News [edited]
http://news.uk.msn.com/health/mad-cow-protein-linked-to-memory


Mad cow protein linked to memory
--------------------------------
A brain protein named as the chief suspect responsible for mad cow disease [variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease] provides a vital function linked to learning and memory, research has shown. Prion protein regulates zinc levels in the brain by assisting its absorption by cells, a study has found. The mineral is thought to play an important role in nerve signalling. But too much zinc build-up between cells has been associated with diseases such as Alzheimer's and Parkinson's diseases.

Scientists have long wondered what the purpose of prion molecules is. All that was clearly known about them was their apparent terrifying ability to transmit "spongiform" brain diseases in both animals and humans. In the cow disease BSE (bovine spongiform encephalopathy) and its human form, variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (vCJD), misshapen rogue prions leave the brain riddled with holes, as in a sponge. They also seem to transmit disease by causing other prions they encounter to become misshapen, in a chain reaction. Disease-causing prions can cling to surgical instruments, or contaminate blood and tissue. Those responsible for vCJD are believed to have spread from cattle to humans through the consumption of infected meat.

Scientists writing in the journal Nature Communications said prion protein helped neurons take up zinc through channels in the cell surface. Professor Nigel Hooper, from the University of Leeds, said: "With ageing, the level of prion protein in our brains falls and less zinc is absorbed by brain cells, which could explain why our memory and learning capabilities change as we get older."

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The report above is based on a paper published in the current issue of Nature Communications: Watt NT, Taylor DR, Kerrigan TL, et al: Prion protein facilitates uptake of zinc into neuronal cells. Nat Commun. 2012 Oct 16; 3(1134). doi: 10.1038/ncomms2135. This is an open access paper accessible at http://www.nature.com/ncomms/journal/v3/n10/full/ncomms2135.html

The conclusion that the loss of PrPC-mediated zinc uptake may in part contribute to the pathogenesis of prion disorders and other neurodegenerative diseases may create a market for design of zinc delivery drugs. - Mod.CP]

